abstract = {Publisher Summary
This chapter reviews descriptive models of thunderstorms or cumulonimbus clouds and attempts to identify several storm types. The cumulonimbus cloud is a convective cloud or cloud system that produces rainfall and lightning. It often produces large hail, severe wind gusts, tornadoes, and heavy rainfall. Cumulonimbus clouds also play an important role in the global energetics and the general circulation of the atmosphere by efficiently transporting moisture and sensible and latent heat into the upper portions of the troposphere and lower stratosphere. They affect the radiative budgets of the troposphere. One of the fundamental properties of a cumulonimbus cloud is the intense, deep updraft associated with the cloud system. The mean updraft speed is controlled by local vertical pressure gradients; buoyancy because of virtual temperature anomalies, pressure anomalies, and the drag or loading because of the presence of liquid or frozen water; turbulent Reynolds stresses; and viscous diffusion and dissipation. Turbulence also distinguishes cumulonimbus clouds. The frequency of lightning discharges does not increase with updraft speeds but is primarily a function of the depth and number of multicellular convective elements in a storm system.}
}